Until recently, in all my years covering Congress, one thing I rarely saw f=
rom
either party was a willingness to give up their institutional and/or consti=
tutional prerogatives=E2=80=94in particular those that endowed them with po=
wer, such as the power of the purse. The one thing the two parties vehement=
ly agreed on was their aversion to even a hint of deference, let alone subj=
ugation, to the executive branch. Then along came Trump.

=C2=A0

I hate to sound partisan, but I do think almost all of the Democrats
in the House and Senate still value the idea of an independent Congress. I=
=E2=80=99ve come to think that, almost with no exceptions, the Republicans =
are no longer an actual political party. They=E2=80=99ve become a cult. If =
they were a political party, they would feel concerned about the institutio=
n that gives them authority suddenly groveling and subjugating itself, as y=
ou say, to one of the branches. Instead, it looks like all they care about =
is not offending Trump, and especially Musk.

A
Separation of Powers
--------------------

On a number of fronts, the Trump administration has issued orders that most
lawyers will tell you are clearly illegal or unconstitutional=E2=80=94where=
 there=E2=80=99s simply no ambiguity. What=E2=80=99s your degree of confide=
nce that the courts will hold the line in those cases?

=C2=A0

We really should assess the centrality of the court. (Not the importance of=
 having courts issue orders that get obeyed. I think that=E2=80=99s importa=
nt to avoid complete chaos.) But
the direction in which the Constitution moves is determined by the court. T=
he idea that the court is the last word has always been problematic, and I =
think we need, over time, to diminish its centrality. But I think it is sti=
ll important that we avoid the kind of chaos in which power is all that mat=
ters, where if you=E2=80=99ve got money like Musk or power like Trump, you=
=E2=80=99ll get away with whatever you do.

=C2=A0

When the
court says, If you=E2=80=99re the president, you won=E2=80=99t be punished =
criminally=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s bad enough, because it really licenses pr=
esidents to go all out. But much worse would be saying, If you=E2=80=99re t=
he president or acting on behalf of the president, nothing any judge says m=
atters. So, I do think it=E2=80=99s important that the courts come through.=
 I think they will in some areas. I think the federal courts=E2=80=94even t=
he ones that are raised on Federalist Society mother=E2=80=99s milk=E2=80=
=94believe not only in the
unitary executive, but in a Congress that has the power of the purse. They=
=E2=80=99ve made it pretty clear in many cases that they take that seriousl=
y. It may be like an irresistible force meeting an immovable object, and wh=
en that happens, we don=E2=80=99t know which way the atoms will split. I th=
ink we can hope. But it will never be the case that the courts alone will s=
ave us. We have to save ourselves. It=E2=80=99s clear that elections matter=
=2E

=C2=A0

It feels to me and a lot of experts like we are headed for a constitutional=
 crisis, where at some point the Supreme Court, despite the perception of m=
any that it=E2=80=99s in the tank for Trump, rules against the administrati=
on on some issue and Trump refuses to comply=E2=80=94essentially saying, =
=E2=80=9COkay, John Roberts, how many divisions have you got?=E2=80=9D What=
 happens then?

=C2=A0

I
think the justices have so convinced themselves of their imperial role that=
 they would basically think that the country would back them up. Whether th=
ey=E2=80=99re right, I don=E2=80=99t know. But what I don=E2=80=99t think t=
hey would do is say, Because we will not be obeyed, we will back down.=C2=
=A0

=C2=A0

Do you agree we=E2=80=99re headed for that kind of crisis? Everything Trump=
 is doing suggests that his belief in his own
authority is total, and he wants to test the proposition and see whether an=
yone or anything can hem him in. And the most obvious next stop on the test=
ing circuit, if Republicans in Congress are going to continue to be supine,=
 is SCOTUS.

=C2=A0

The U.S. government had a pretty bad record under Trump before the court. W=
hen he was rebuffed by the Supreme Court, he didn=E2=80=99t hesitate to say=
, They=E2=80=99re wrong; they don=E2=80=99t know
what the hell they=E2=80=99re talking about. So I think he would say that, =
and he would say they=E2=80=99re exceeding their jurisdiction. His speechwr=
iters would give him a way of saying that the court should be ignored. And =
that would be a major crisis.

