ll in office, of course, but it=E2=80=99s a matter of time until she=E2=80=
=99s confirmed as ambassador to the United Nations. Although no one=E2=80=
=99s predicting an upset this spring, political observers will be focused o=
n the <em>margin</em>, and what kind of trouble it portends for Republicans=
 in the midterms.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The special election will probably ta=
ke place in
April, by which point we could be in the midst of a prolonged government sh=
utdown and a looming national default. Tariffs could be slamming New York=
=E2=80=99s farmers, and the average American could be feeling the downstrea=
m effects of <strong>Elon</strong>=E2=80=99s sweeping DOGE cuts, if they=E2=
=80=99re implemented. Meanwhile, SALT will be <em>the</em> controversy in N=
ew York as Capitol Hill Republicans sort through the tax cuts bill. Stefani=
k=E2=80=99s strength as an incumbent is unquestioned; she won reelection 62
percent to 38 percent, and 24 points is a <em>huge</em> buffer for any Repu=
blican running to succeed her. But that=E2=80=99s also the exact margin by =
which former Rep. <strong>Tom Price</strong> of Georgia won his 2016 reelec=
tion. After Trump appointed Price to the cabinet, Democratic unknown <stron=
g>Jon Ossoff</strong> started to gain traction in his district. Ossoff ende=
d up losing the race to succeed Price by a mere four points=E2=80=94a shock=
ingly narrow margin for what had been considered a safe Republican
seat=E2=80=94ultimately foreshadowing the 2018 Democratic midterm wave.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">S=
ure, it=E2=80=99s not a perfect comparison. On election night 2016, it was =
apparent the suburbs were moving toward the Democrats, despite <strong>Hill=
ary Clinton</strong>=E2=80=99s loss. Price=E2=80=99s district, a suburban o=
ne outside Atlanta, exemplified that pattern. On the other hand, there were=
 no silver linings for Dems in 2024, and it was an <em>especially</em> roug=
h night in
rural districts like New York=E2=80=99s 21st. So while Democrats are not co=
unting on this special election to minimize <strong>Mike Johnson</strong>=
=E2=80=99s House margin, the question for now is whether they will lose <em=
>less badly</em>=E2=80=94and whether that=E2=80=99s a step in the flailing =
party=E2=80=99s journey back to some semblance of confidence.=C2=A0</p></di=
