dding-right:24px;text-align:center;width:100%;"><h3 style=3D"margin:0;color=
:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;PuckSerifDisplay&#39;,&#39;Georgia&=
#39;;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:normal;line-height:120%;=
text-align:center;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;mso-line-height-alt:28.79999=
9999999997px;"><strong>Crossing
the Rubicon</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;"><strong><em>John Heilemann</em></strong><strong>: Yale historian and sc=
holar of
authoritarianism Timothy Snyder wrote the other day, about what Team Trump =
is doing, =E2=80=9COf course it=E2=80=99s a coup.=E2=80=9D Do you agree?</s=
trong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Laurence Tribe</em>: I think it is obviously=
 a coup, an inside coup, and not only by people in power who are now consol=
idating their power, but by people who were never elected to power. It <em>=
has</em> to be called a coup because it meets all the criteria; it is an
attempt to use the instruments of power to displace the entire structure of=
 government that we have nurtured and inherited over two centuries. And it=
=E2=80=99s happening at blinding speed, so it=E2=80=99s very hard to see ex=
actly where it=E2=80=99s going.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">One of the surprising t=
hings is that it=E2=80=99s happening so quickly and with so little systemat=
ic planning that it is quite possible that it will collapse on itself. Cour=
ts, one
after another, are going to strike this stuff down; we see it all the time.=
 The legal questions are easy, and that=E2=80=99s one of the things that ma=
kes the situation so strange. It=E2=80=99s not as though there are exotic, =
difficult legal questions. I think there=E2=80=99s a good chance that even =
the handpicked Supreme Court that Trump is counting on to allow these thing=
s to go forward will say, <em>No, that=E2=80=99s a bridge too far</em>. And=
 then what? That=E2=80=99ll be a fork in the road. On one hand, Trump may d=
ismiss anything
the courts say. And because, thanks partly to him, the courts have lost lot=
s of their credibility, it may be that Trump can get away with that, and th=
at will mean that we really don=E2=80=99t have a legal system anymore. On t=
he other hand, he [could] obey the courts, blame them, and say that they=E2=
=80=99re part of what we have to displace. Either way, it=E2=80=99s going t=
o be chaos.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>What do you say to those who =
say
that talk of coups, at least at this stage, is little more than liberal hyp=
erbolizing, catastrophizing, or both?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">You have to define what yo=
u think the United States of America is. Is it whatever happens as a result=
 of an election, as long as people are warned? Or is it something that has =
certain structural characteristics? It=E2=80=99s not important what label y=
ou give it. What [is happening] is a complete tossing aside of
