<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;"><strong>Until recently, in all my years covering Congress, one thing I =
rarely saw from
either party was a willingness to give up their institutional and/or consti=
tutional prerogatives=E2=80=94in particular those that endowed them with po=
wer, such as the power of the purse. The one thing the two parties vehement=
ly agreed on was their aversion to even a hint of deference, let alone subj=
ugation, to the executive branch. Then along came Trump.</strong></p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">I hate =
to sound partisan, but I do think almost all of the Democrats
in the House and Senate still value the idea of an independent Congress. I=
=E2=80=99ve come to think that, almost with no exceptions, the Republicans =
are no longer an actual political party. They=E2=80=99ve become a cult. If =
they were a political party, they would feel concerned about the institutio=
n that gives them authority suddenly groveling and subjugating itself, as y=
ou say, to one of the branches. Instead, it looks like all they care about =
is not offending Trump, and especially Musk.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table class=3D"g oq" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspa=
