9999999997px;"><strong>A
Separation of Powers</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;"><strong>On a number of fronts, the Trump administration has issued orde=
rs that most
lawyers will tell you are </strong><strong><em>clearly </em></strong><stron=
g>illegal or unconstitutional=E2=80=94where there=E2=80=99s simply no ambig=
uity. What=E2=80=99s your degree of confidence that the courts will hold th=
e line in those cases?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">We really should assess=
 the centrality of the court. (Not the importance of having courts issue or=
ders that get obeyed. I think that=E2=80=99s important to avoid complete ch=
aos.) But
the direction in which the Constitution moves is determined by the court. T=
he idea that the court is the last word has always been problematic, and I =
think we need, over time, to diminish its centrality. But I think it is sti=
ll important that we avoid the kind of chaos in which power is all that mat=
ters, where if you=E2=80=99ve got money like Musk or power like Trump, you=
=E2=80=99ll get away with whatever you do.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">When the
court says, <em>If you=E2=80=99re the president, you won=E2=80=99t be punis=
hed criminally</em>=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s bad enough, because it really li=
censes presidents to go all out. But much worse would be saying, <em>If you=
=E2=80=99re the president or acting on behalf of the president, nothing any=
 judge says matters</em>. So, I do think it=E2=80=99s important that the co=
urts come through. I think they will in some areas. I think the federal cou=
rts=E2=80=94even the ones that are raised on Federalist Society mother=E2=
=80=99s milk=E2=80=94believe not only in the
unitary executive, but in a Congress that has the power of the purse. They=
=E2=80=99ve made it pretty clear in many cases that they take that seriousl=
y. It may be like an irresistible force meeting an immovable object, and wh=
en that happens, we don=E2=80=99t know which way the atoms will split. I th=
ink we can hope. But it will <em>never</em> be the case that the courts alo=
ne will save us. We have to save ourselves. It=E2=80=99s clear that electio=
ns matter.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>It feels to me and a lot of expert=
s like we are headed for a constitutional crisis, where at some point the S=
upreme Court, despite the perception of many that it=E2=80=99s in the tank =
for Trump, rules against the administration on some issue and Trump refuses=
 to comply=E2=80=94essentially saying, =E2=80=9COkay, John Roberts, how man=
y divisions have you got?=E2=80=9D What happens then?</strong></p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">I
think the justices have so convinced themselves of their imperial role that=
 they would basically think that the country would back them up. Whether th=
ey=E2=80=99re right, I don=E2=80=99t know. But what I don=E2=80=99t think t=
hey would do is say, <em>Because we will not be obeyed, we will back down</=
em>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Do you agree we=E2=80=99re headed =
for that kind of crisis? Everything Trump is doing suggests that his belief=
 in his own
authority is total, and he wants to test the proposition and see whether an=
yone or anything can hem him in. And the most obvious next stop on the test=
ing circuit, if Republicans in Congress are going to continue to be supine,=
 is SCOTUS.</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;">The U.S. government had a pretty bad record under Tr=
ump before the court. When he was rebuffed by the Supreme Court, he didn=E2=
=80=99t hesitate to say, <em>They=E2=80=99re wrong; they don=E2=80=99t know
what the hell they=E2=80=99re talking about</em>. So I think he would say t=
hat, and he would say they=E2=80=99re exceeding their jurisdiction. His spe=
echwriters would give him a way of saying that the court should be ignored.=
 And that would be a major crisis.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
